THE ART OF POETRY.

Tnnsr: remarks upon the art of poetry were probably de- signed as the third epistle of the second book, and addressed to Lucius Piso and his two sons. Horace did not pretend to give a complete treatise upon the art of poetry3 but to throw out such hints upon the leading topics of the subject, as the na- ture of an epistle would allow. He has therefore observed no particular method or order in discussing the subject3 nor been at the trouble of making any preamble. He begins at once with the most essential, necessary, and important precept, which is unity and simplicity of design.
